{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -c \"sed -n '1,220p' frontend/calculator-writeup.html\"","aggregated_output":"<!doctype html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n  <head>\n    <meta charset=\"utf-8\" />\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width,initial-scale=1\" />\n    <title>A Frontend Loop Needs a Real App</title>\n    <meta\n      name=\"description\"\n      content=\"Why an AI VRAM calculator — not a todo list — is the right target for an agent loop that writes frontend code.\"\n    />\n    <script src=\"/scripts/calculator-writeup-styles.js\"></script>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n    <div class=\"page\">\n      <div class=\"topbar\">\n        <a class=\"site-link\" href=\"/\">Rox dT</a>\n        <a class=\"site-link\" href=\"https://aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app/\"\n          >Try the calculator &rarr;</a\n        >\n      </div>\n\n      <header class=\"masthead\">\n        <p class=\"eyebrow\">Field Notes &middot; On Loops</p>\n        <h1>A Frontend Loop Needs a Real App</h1>\n        <p class=\"sub\">\n          I built an AI VRAM calculator in TypeScript to test frontend agent\n          loops. It was the right kind of mistake.\n        </p>\n        <p class=\"byline\">\n          <span>By Roxana del Toro</span>\n          <span>Loop engineering</span>\n          <span>Calculator, not todo</span>\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class=\"flow\">\n        <p class=\"lead\">\n          I built an AI VRAM calculator because I needed a sample app for\n          TypeScript frontend loops. That turned out to be the right kind of\n          mistake: calculators force generated frontends to deal with real\n          state, real math, real copy, and real edge cases.\n        </p>\n\n        <p>\n          The app is live at\n          <a href=\"https://aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app/\"\n            >aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app</a\n          >. You give it a model size, precision, workload, and deployment mode;\n          it gives you a VRAM estimate, a hardware tier, a rough speed, and the\n          assumptions it used to get there. Everything runs in the browser.\n          There is no backend.\n        </p>\n\n        <p>\n          This post is about why that app &mdash; and not a todo list &mdash; is\n          the right target for an agent loop that writes frontend code.\n        </p>\n\n        <h2>\n          <span class=\"kicker\">Why this app</span>The domain supplies the rigor\n        </h2>\n        <p>\n          VRAM estimation is a real question people ask before spending real\n          money. &ldquo;Will a 70B model fit on the GPU I&rsquo;m about to\n          buy?&rdquo; has a checkable answer, and getting it wrong is\n          embarrassing in a way a mislabeled todo item never is.\n        </p>\n        <p>\n          More importantly for a loop benchmark, the domain has\n          <em>naturally</em> interacting inputs: model size, precision,\n          quantization overhead, context window, batch size, KV-cache precision,\n          execution mode (inference vs LoRA vs QLoRA vs full training), MoE\n          routing, memory sharding. These aren&rsquo;t invented complexity\n          &mdash; they&rsquo;re the actual variables of the actual problem, and\n          they interact. QLoRA pins you to 4-bit. Training modes hide\n          inference-only fields. MoE changes speed but not resident memory. A\n          Local/Edge profile that outgrows every consumer card needs to\n          <em>say so</em> instead of cheerfully recommending a datacenter\n          accelerator.\n        </p>\n\n        <blockquote class=\"pull\">\n          <p>\n            A loop can fake its way through a todo app. It cannot fake its way\n            through this.\n          </p>\n        </blockquote>\n\n        <h2>\n          <span class=\"kicker\">Why it beats a todo app</span>The failures are\n          visible\n        </h2>\n        <ul class=\"notes\">\n          <li>\n            <strong>Incorrect math is visible.</strong> 70B at fp16 is 140 GB of\n            weights; AdamW mixed precision is ~16 bytes per parameter. Anyone in\n            the field can eyeball the output &mdash; and so does the parity\n            suite, which drives four canonical scenarios through real browser\n            controls.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>The UI complexity is natural.</strong> The uncheck path of a\n            checkbox whose default is <code>true</code> was a real bug: HTML\n            forms omit unchecked boxes, normalization fell back to the default,\n            and Gradient Checkpointing could never be turned off. Tests passed,\n            the gate was green, and the bug shipped &mdash; because nobody wrote\n            the <em>uncheck</em> test.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Tests matter because money does.</strong> People may buy\n            hardware based on this output. That reframes 100% branch coverage\n            from vanity metric to floor.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Accessibility is the product.</strong> The suite runs six\n            browser projects, phone to 2560px. That matrix caught a WebKit bug:\n            Safari never restyles a sibling when a\n            <code>&lt;meter&gt;</code> attribute changes, so the fit meter\n            stayed wrong for every real Safari user while Chrome looked perfect.\n          </li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <h2>\n          <span class=\"kicker\">What the loop taught</span>Specs, gates, and copy\n        </h2>\n        <ul class=\"notes\">\n          <li>\n            <strong>Specs beat vibes.</strong> Every behavior worth having was\n            written down before it was generated; the ones that weren&rsquo;t\n            are the ones that churned.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Gates catch boring, real issues.</strong> Eighteen checks\n            &mdash; prettier, eslint, stylelint, typecheck, semgrep,\n            100%-coverage units, the full Playwright matrix, Lighthouse budgets.\n            Almost nothing it rejected was interesting. All of it was real.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Copy is product logic when numbers are uncertain.</strong>\n            &ldquo;Fits on one 24 GB card: 19.0 GB uses 93% of its 20.4 GB\n            usable VRAM&rdquo; took more revisions than the math. An estimate\n            without its assumptions is indistinguishable from a wrong one.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Quality drifts upward when checks are strict.</strong> The\n            gate refuses lint bypass comments, unstages forbidden paths at\n            commit, runs the whole matrix on every push. &ldquo;Demo app&rdquo;\n            stopped being accurate without anyone deciding it should.\n          </li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <h2>\n          <span class=\"kicker\">The takeaway</span>Pick a product-shaped target\n        </h2>\n        <p>\n          Good frontend agent loops need a product-shaped target: something with\n          state that interacts, math that can be checked, copy that carries\n          meaning, and users who would notice. A calculator is a cheat code\n          &mdash; the domain supplies the rigor, and the loop either meets it or\n          fails visibly.\n        </p>\n        <p>\n          This one ended up as both: a tool I actually use before recommending\n          hardware, and the proving ground that shaped\n          <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/loopgate-harness\">LoopGate</a\n          >&rsquo;s checks. The todo app never stood a chance.\n        </p>\n      </div>\n\n      <p class=\"colophon\">\n        The calculator is live at\n        <a href=\"https://aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app/\"\n          ><strong>aideploymentcalculator.vercel.app</strong></a\n        >; source at\n        <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/ai_deployment_calculator\"\n          >rxdt/ai_deployment_calculator</a\n        >. The harness it hardened:\n        <a href=\"https://github.com/rxdt/loopgate-harness\"\n          >rxdt/loopgate-harness</a\n        >. <br /><a href=\"/\">Back to Rox dT</a>\n      </p>\n    </div>\n  </body>\n</html>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
