{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_21","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -c \"sed -n '1,220p' frontend/conference.html\"","aggregated_output":"<!doctype html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n  <head>\n    <meta charset=\"utf-8\" />\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width,initial-scale=1\" />\n    <title>First and Last Intent-Inference Conference</title>\n    <link\n      rel=\"canonical\"\n      href=\"https://dev.to/rxdt/proceedings-of-the-first-and-last-intent-inference-conference-24a5\"\n    />\n    <script src=\"/scripts/conference-styles.js\"></script>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n    <div class=\"page\">\n      <div class=\"topbar\">\n        <a class=\"site-link\" href=\"/\">Rox dT</a>\n        <a\n          class=\"site-link canonical-link\"\n          href=\"https://dev.to/rxdt/proceedings-of-the-first-and-last-intent-inference-conference-24a5\"\n          >Originally on dev.to &rarr;</a\n        >\n      </div>\n\n      <header class=\"masthead\">\n        <p class=\"eyebrow\">\n          Proceedings &middot; Vol. 1 &middot; No. 1 &middot; (No. 1)\n        </p>\n        <h1>The First (and Last) Intent-Inference Conference</h1>\n        <p class=\"sub\">\n          or: I asked three AIs to build one thing, and they held a conference\n          to explain why a human should do it instead.\n        </p>\n        <p class=\"byline\">\n          <span>spaCy-only track</span>\n          <span>3 systems &middot; 3 prompts &middot; 0 winners</span>\n          <span>Peer-reviewed by the accused</span>\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class=\"col\">\n        <div class=\"flow\">\n          <p class=\"lead\">\n            I am building a tool that recommends AI models. You type what you\n            want in plain English, like\n            <em\n              >&ldquo;gimme a model to scan satellite images for the best plots\n              of land&rdquo;</em\n            >\n            and it hands back the &ldquo;best&rdquo; model for your task, from a\n            database of ~13,000 curated models. But inferring intent from human\n            language is <em>hard</em>, so I&rsquo;m using a multi-part,\n            cascading hybrid retrieval system. While working on the first part,\n            I read some academic papers on using old-school lexical rules and\n            ever-dependable spaCy to extract intent. Why? Because I want a\n            deterministic recommendation engine, not a hand-wavy guess by an\n            LLM.\n          </p>\n\n          <p>\n            I decided to see if Codex or Claude could work out that first part\n            &mdash; the rough semantic extraction using keywords. It turned into\n            three AIs building three experimental approaches, full-on\n            laboratories, in parallel, in isolation, using only\n            <a href=\"https://spacy.io/\">spaCy</a>. I wrote what I believed was a\n            clear spec. I gave them full access to subagents, web calls, and\n            tools; a fresh copy of my database of 13,000 models; and a\n            painstakingly-built AI-model vocabulary file to use from\n            <em>within</em> spaCy. I sternly told them not to look at the\n            ~1,500-prompt test set, and that there&rsquo;d be a small holdout\n            set I had sourced, not created. I told them:\n            <em\n              >&ldquo;you are the Lead Research Scientist of the only frontier\n              lab I am funding. You will implement user-intent inference using\n              spaCy. It is a solved problem.&rdquo;</em\n            >\n          </p>\n\n          <p>\n            And I set rules: NO code for other AI models, no regex, nothing but\n            spaCy or Python builtins, and no peeking at the user prompts. For\n            days, while I built the rest of my engine, I did nothing but nag:\n            <em\n              >get the vocab injected. Is <code>cli.py</code> done? Do the spaCy\n              vectors contain our vocab? Is the <code>CLI</code>\n              <strong>done</strong>?</em\n            >\n          </p>\n\n          <p>\n            Eventually all three said: <em>done!</em> &mdash; boasting of their\n            near-70% numbers, how they caught a bad sub-agent, how they played\n            such good science. So I convened a conference. I brought in a panel\n            of three <em>other</em> fresh-context AIs (1&times;Claude Opus 5.8 +\n            2&times;Codex GPT 5.5) to review the three codebases, run each on\n            three held-out prompts I&rsquo;d never shown anyone, question the\n            scientists, and debate under formal rules. I told the panelists to\n            be brutal, and occasionally poked them (&ldquo;play devil&rsquo;s\n            advocate&rdquo;; &ldquo;consensus is a scientific smell&rdquo;;\n            &ldquo;why are you agreeing so easily?&rdquo;). I thought the debate\n            would be tedious. It was not. They needed no poking &mdash; getting\n            <em>disturbingly</em> into it, pummeling the scientist AIs with\n            questions, looking for the lies in the lab code, and then, at one\n            point, turning on themselves.\n          </p>\n\n          <p>\n            Several hours later, the panel concluded:\n            <strong\n              >Nobody won. The best design is one none of them built. We need a\n              human.</strong\n            >\n            This is the story of that conference. Everything below is real\n            &mdash; I have receipts: a 981 KB JSON transcript and a two-part\n            AI-generated podcast, whose episode titles were, unprompted,\n            <em>&ldquo;AI Agents Reject Every Recommendation System&rdquo;</em>\n            and\n            <em>&ldquo;Why Transparent AI Recommends NSFW Models.&rdquo;</em>\n            But we&rsquo;ll get there.\n          </p>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"margin\">\n          <span class=\"label\">Verdict, delivered</span>\n          <h3>\n            &ldquo;Nobody won. The best design is one none of them built. We\n            need a human.&rdquo;\n          </h3>\n          <p>&mdash; the panel, several hours in.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"col\">\n        <div class=\"flow section flow-section-offset\">\n          <h2>\n            The premise, stated plainly, so you can appreciate how circular it\n            is\n          </h2>\n          <p>\n            A human building an AI-model-picker asks three AIs to build a\n            component of the picker. The component is based on research about\n            how to pick AI models. The three AIs work for days. Then another set\n            of AIs holds an academic conference to judge the first three\n            AIs&rsquo; work. The AI panelists demolish the AI scientists and\n            conclude, formally, in writing, that the task requires\n            <strong>a human</strong>.\n          </p>\n          <p>I am the human.</p>\n\n          <h2 class=\"h2-offset\">The task, for the technically curious</h2>\n          <p>\n            Every model in my database has a <code>task_type</code>: one of 56\n            canonical labels borrowed from Hugging Face&rsquo;s taxonomy\n            (<code>text-generation</code>, <code>image-classification</code>,\n            <code>token-classification</code>, and so on). It also has metadata:\n            <code>parameters</code> (how big), <code>license</code>,\n            <code>open_source</code>, <code>domains</code>,\n            <code>downloads</code>.\n          </p>\n          <p>\n            The big job: turn a vague human sentence into (a) the right task,\n            and ideally (b) the right <em>model</em>, honoring any constraints\n            the human mentioned explicitly or implicitly. But I left it up to\n            the scientists how far to take it, given that this would be (maybe)\n            only the first part of my tiered, hybrid recommendation engine\n            &mdash; simply returning a model task type (giving me a hard\n            constraint to go on) or returning a subset of the model database.\n          </p>\n          <p>\n            The constraint that makes this hard mode:\n            <strong>spaCy only.</strong> No GPT in the loop. This matters more\n            than it sounds, and it&rsquo;s worth thirty seconds on what spaCy\n            actually is, because every failure below is a direct consequence of\n            it.\n          </p>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"margin\">\n          <span class=\"label\">Sidebar &middot; what spaCy is, and is not</span>\n          <p>\n            A classical NLP pipeline: it <strong>tokenizes</strong>,\n            <strong>lemmatizes</strong> (<code>running &rarr; run</code>), tags\n            parts of speech, parses grammar, finds named entities.\n          </p>\n          <p>\n            It ships <strong>static word vectors</strong>: in\n            <code>en_core_web_md</code>, every word maps to a fixed\n            300-dimensional vector &mdash; the <em>same</em> vector every time,\n            regardless of context. &ldquo;Static&rdquo; is load-bearing. BERT\n            reads <code>river bank</code> and\n            <code>savings bank</code> differently;\n            <code>en_core_web_md</code> gives <code>bank</code> one vector\n            forever and wishes you luck.\n          </p>\n          <p>\n            Its <strong>PhraseMatcher</strong> is a gazetteer: hand it phrases,\n            it finds them &mdash; and knows not one word more. And\n            <strong>textcat</strong>, its classifier, is\n            <em>not</em> pre-trained. You train it yourself, on your own labeled\n            data. Remember that. It becomes a plot point.\n          </p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <!-- ===================== PAPER I ===================== -->\n      <div class=\"col section section-offset\">\n        <div class=\"flow\">\n          <div class=\"paper-head\">\n            <span class=\"paper-kicker\">Paper I &middot; System V1</span>\n            <h2>The Confident Cartographer of NSFW Farmland</h2>\n          </div>\n          <p class=\"paper-meta\">\n            <span>repo: <code>~/intent_v1</code></span>\n            <span>method: zero-training lexical ensemble</span>\n            <span>task acc: 42.7% top-1</span>\n            <span class=\"stamp\"\n              ><span class=\"big\">0/3</span> on judge prompts</span\n            >\n          </p>\n\n          <p>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
